📝 GitHub Journal: Day 08 - Automated Stack Provisioning
Project Overview

Today’s objective was to automate the setup of a multi-tier Java application stack (vProfile) using Vagrant and Bash Scripts. Instead of manually configuring each server, I used infrastructure-as-code principles to deploy five distinct virtual machines.
Infrastructure Architecture

I provisioned the following environment:

    Database (db01): MariaDB on CentOS Stream 9.

    Memcached (mc01): Distributed memory caching system on CentOS Stream 9.

    RabbitMQ (rmq01): Message broker for asynchronous tasks on CentOS Stream 9.

    Application Server (app01): Apache Tomcat for running the Java application.

    Web Server (web01): Nginx acting as a Reverse Proxy on Ubuntu 22.04.

Key Tasks & Challenges

    Multi-VM Configuration: Configured a complex Vagrantfile to handle different Operating Systems (CentOS and Ubuntu) and private networking.

    Automated Scripting: Wrote and executed shell scripts to automate the installation of MariaDB, Nginx, and system dependencies.

    Network Troubleshooting: Encountered a common issue where the OS renamed the network interface to enp0s8 instead of eth1. I successfully debugged this using ip addr to identify the correct private IP (192.168.56.11).

    Resource Management: Managed host RAM and CPU limits to ensure 5 VMs could boot simultaneously without crashing the hypervisor.

Commands Used

    vagrant up: To trigger the automated build.

    vagrant ssh [vm_name]: To log in and verify services.

    ip addr show: To confirm private network IP assignments.

    systemctl status [service]: To ensure Nginx and MariaDB were running correctly.

Outcome

The environment is fully reachable. The Nginx server is successfully listening on the private network, and the database has been initialized with the project schema.
